    <div class="container">
        <header>
            <h1>HTML Codes Reference</h1>
            <p class="subtitle">A comprehensive guide to HTML elements with examples and explanations</p>
            
            <div class="search-box">
                <input type="text" id="search" placeholder="Search HTML elements...">
            </div>
            
            <div class="category-filter">
                <button class="category-btn active">All</button>
                <button class="category-btn">Text</button>
                <button class="category-btn">Media</button>
                <button class="category-btn">Forms</button>
                <button class="category-btn">Semantic</button>
            </div>
        </header>
        
        <div class="grid">
            <!-- Heading Elements -->
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <h2>Headings</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <div class="code-example">
                        &lt;h1&gt;Heading 1&lt;/h1&gt;<br>
                        &lt;h2&gt;Heading 2&lt;/h2&gt;<br>
                        &lt;h3&gt;Heading 3&lt;/h3&gt;<br>
                        &lt;h4&gt;Heading 4&lt;/h4&gt;<br>
                        &lt;h5&gt;Heading 5&lt;/h5&gt;<br>
                        &lt;h6&gt;Heading 6&lt;/h6&gt;
                    </div>
                    <div class="explanation">
                        HTML provides six levels of heading elements. &lt;h1&gt; is the highest level and &lt;h6&gt; is the lowest.
                    </div>
                    <div class="output">
                        <h4>Output:</h4>
                        <h1 style="font-size: 22px; margin: 5px 0;">Heading 1</h1>
                        <h2 style="font-size: 20px; margin: 5px 0;">Heading 2</h2>
                        <h3 style="font-size: 18px; margin: 5px 0;">Heading 3</h3>
                        <h4 style="font-size: 16px; margin: 5px 0;">Heading 4</h4>
                        <h5 style="font-size: 14px; margin: 5px 0;">Heading 5</h5>
                        <h6 style="font-size: 12px; margin: 5px 0;">Heading 6</h6>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Paragraph -->
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <h2>Paragraphs</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <div class="code-example">
                        &lt;p&gt;This is a paragraph. HTML paragraphs are used to structure text content into blocks.&lt;/p&gt;<br>
                        &lt;p&gt;This is another paragraph with &lt;strong&gt;bold text&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;em&gt;italic text&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
                    </div>
                    <div class="explanation">
                        The &lt;p&gt; element defines a paragraph. Browsers automatically add margin to paragraphs.
                    </div>
                    <div class="output">
                        <h4>Output:</h4>
                        <p>This is a paragraph. HTML paragraphs are used to structure text content into blocks.</p>
                        <p>This is another paragraph with <strong>bold text</strong> and <em>italic text</em>.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Links -->
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <h2>Links</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <div class="code-example">
                        &lt;a href="https://www.example.com"&gt;Visit Example.com&lt;/a&gt;<br>
                        &lt;a href="about.html" target="_blank"&gt;Open About Page (new tab)&lt;/a&gt;<br>
                        &lt;a href="#section1"&gt;Jump to Section 1&lt;/a&gt;
                    </div>
                    <div class="explanation">
                        The &lt;a&gt; element defines a hyperlink. The <code>href</code> attribute specifies the URL. Use <code>target="_blank"</code> to open in a new tab.
                    </div>
                    <div class="output">
                        <h4>Output:</h4>
                        <a href="#" style="color: #4a69bd;">Visit Example.com</a><br>
                        <a href="#" style="color: #4a69bd;">Open About Page (new tab)</a><br>
                        <a href="#" style="color: #4a69bd;">Jump to Section 1</a>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Lists -->
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <h2>Lists</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <div class="code-example">
                        &lt;ul&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li&gt;Unordered list item 1&lt;/li&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li&gt;Unordered list item 2&lt;/li&gt;<br>
                        &lt;/ul&gt;<br><br>
                        &lt;ol&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li&gt;Ordered list item 1&lt;/li&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;li&gt;Ordered list item 2&lt;/li&gt;<br>
                        &lt;/ol&gt;
                    </div>
                    <div class="explanation">
                        &lt;ul&gt; creates an unordered list (bulleted), &lt;ol&gt; creates an ordered list (numbered). Each list item is defined with &lt;li&gt;.
                    </div>
                    <div class="output">
                        <h4>Output:</h4>
                        <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                            <li>Unordered list item 1</li>
                            <li>Unordered list item 2</li>
                        </ul>
                        <ol style="margin-left: 20px;">
                            <li>Ordered list item 1</li>
                            <li>Ordered list item 2</li>
                        </ol>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Images -->
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <h2>Images</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <div class="code-example">
                        &lt;img src="image.jpg" alt="Description of image"&gt;<br>
                        &lt;img src="photo.png" alt="A beautiful landscape" width="400" height="300"&gt;
                    </div>
                    <div class="explanation">
                        The &lt;img&gt; element is used to embed images. The <code>src</code> attribute specifies the image path, and <code>alt</code> provides alternative text for accessibility.
                    </div>
                    <div class="output">
                        <h4>Output:</h4>
                        <div style="background-color: #e0e0e0; padding: 20px; text-align: center; border-radius: 5px;">
                            [Image Placeholder]
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Forms -->
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <h2>Forms</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <div class="code-example">
                        &lt;form action="/submit" method="post"&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;label for="name"&gt;Name:&lt;/label&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;input type="text" id="name" name="name"&gt;&lt;br&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;label for="email"&gt;Email:&lt;/label&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;input type="email" id="email" name="email"&gt;&lt;br&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;input type="submit" value="Submit"&gt;<br>
                        &lt;/form&gt;
                    </div>
                    <div class="explanation">
                        The &lt;form&gt; element creates a form for user input. &lt;input&gt; elements define form fields, and &lt;label&gt; provides labels for them.
                    </div>
                    <div class="output">
                        <h4>Output:</h4>
                        <form style="background-color: #f8f9fa; padding: 15px; border-radius: 5px;">
                            <label for="name-demo">Name:</label><br>
                            <input type="text" id="name-demo" name="name" style="margin-bottom: 10px; padding: 5px; width: 100%;"><br>
                            <label for="email-demo">Email:</label><br>
                            <input type="email" id="email-demo" name="email" style="margin-bottom: 10px; padding: 5px; width: 100%;"><br>
                            <input type="submit" value="Submit" style="background-color: #4a69bd; color: white; border: none; padding: 8px 16px; border-radius: 4px;">
                        </form>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Tables -->
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <h2>Tables</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <div class="code-example">
                        &lt;table&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;tr&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;th&gt;Name&lt;/th&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;th&gt;Age&lt;/th&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/tr&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;tr&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;td&gt;John&lt;/td&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;td&gt;25&lt;/td&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/tr&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;tr&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;td&gt;Jane&lt;/td&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;td&gt;30&lt;/td&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/tr&gt;<br>
                        &lt;/table&gt;
                    </div>
                    <div class="explanation">
                        The &lt;table&gt; element creates a table. &lt;tr&gt; defines table rows, &lt;th&gt; defines header cells, and &lt;td&gt; defines standard cells.
                    </div>
                    <div class="output">
                        <h4>Output:</h4>
                        <table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse;">
                            <tr style="background-color: #4a69bd; color: white;">
                                <th style="padding: 8px; text-align: left; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Name</th>
                                <th style="padding: 8px; text-align: left; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Age</th>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">John</td>
                                <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">25</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr style="background-color: #f2f2f2;">
                                <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">Jane</td>
                                <td style="padding: 8px; border: 1px solid #ddd;">30</td>
                            </tr>
                        </table>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <!-- Semantic Elements -->
            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">
                    <h2>Semantic HTML</h2>
                </div>
                <div class="card-body">
                    <div class="code-example">
                        &lt;header&gt;Header content&lt;/header&gt;<br>
                        &lt;nav&gt;Navigation links&lt;/nav&gt;<br>
                        &lt;main&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;article&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;section&gt;Section content&lt;/section&gt;<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/article&gt;<br>
                        &lt;/main&gt;<br>
                        &lt;footer&gt;Footer content&lt;/footer&gt;
                    </div>
                    <div class="explanation">
                        Semantic elements clearly describe their meaning to both the browser and developer. Examples include &lt;header&gt;, &lt;nav&gt;, &lt;main&gt;, &lt;section&gt;, &lt;article&gt;, and &lt;footer&gt;.
                    </div>
                    <div class="output">
                        <h4>Output:</h4>
                        <div style="border: 1px solid #ddd; padding: 10px;">
                            <div style="background: #e0e0e0; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px;">Header content</div>
                            <div style="background: #d0d0d0; padding: 10px; margin-bottom
